body:
Given the following code ([Playground](https://play.rust-lang.org/?version=nightly&mode=debug&edition=2021&gist=c8e217552cdc94e049a6c441e226cdaf)):

```rust
struct NonCopy;

fn test(_x: NonCopy) -> bool { false }

fn main() {
    let x = NonCopy;

    match 0 {
        1 | -1 if test(x) => {}
        _ => {}
    }
}
```

The current output is:

```
error[E0382]: use of moved value: `x`
 --> src/main.rs:9:24
  |
6 |     let x = NonCopy;
  |         - move occurs because `x` has type `NonCopy`, which does not implement the `Copy` trait
...
9 |         1 | -1 if test(x) => {}
  |                        ^ value used here after move
  |
note: consider changing this parameter type in function `test` to borrow instead if owning the value isn't necessary
 --> src/main.rs:3:13
  |
3 | fn test(_x: NonCopy) -> bool { false }
  |    ----     ^^^^^^^ this parameter takes ownership of the value
  |    |
  |    in this function
```

This happens because the guard is executed multiple times for an or-pattern. Maybe this should be explained in the diagnostic, similar to the diagnostic emitted in loops ("value moved in previous iteration of loop")?

